sim <- metasims(single_study = TRUE)

## performing  18  simulations of  3  trials
sim_parameter <- function(sim, arg){

  sim %>% 
    purrr::pluck("arguments") %>% 
    dplyr::filter(argument == arg) %>% 
    purrr::pluck("value")
}
# parameters 
(unequal_effect_ratio <- sim %>% sim_parameter("unequal_effect_ratio") %>% 
   as.numeric())
## [1] 1.2
trials <- sim %>% sim_parameter("trials") %>% as.numeric()

distributions caption

  1. Data for the control and intervention arms were sampled from distributions: the normal distribution, with parameters 2 and 0.3, the exponential distribution, with parameters 2, the Pareto distribution, with parameters 3 and 3, the Pareto distribution, with parameters 2 and 1, the Pareto distribution, with parameters 0.5 and 1, the log-normal distribution, with parameters 1 and 0.3.

plot caption

  1. These simulation results are summarised by the proportion, coverage, of 3 confidence intervals that contain the true measure \(\nu\), or log-ratio \(\log(\rho)\) of control \(\nu_C\) and intervention \(\nu_I\) measures, with \(\rho := \nu_I/\nu_C\).

Caption for the simulation

The case where the control median \(\nu_C\) is equal to the intervention median \(\nu_I\) is considered, \(\rho= 1\), as is an unequal ratio, \(\rho =\) 1.2.

Data for the control and intervention arms sampled from distributions in accompanying Distributions plot.

Summary statistics were calculated from the samples, for the estimator of the variance \(\mathcal V(m)\) of the sample median.

meta-analysis only

For each of the 3 trials, \(K\) studies’ control and intervention arms were simulated. A meta-analysis was performed via metafor::rma with the Knapp-Hartung test for… todo:. The confidence interval that informs the coverage was extracted from the model results.

Simulations, 3 trials, were performed for each of \(K =\) 3, 7, 10 studies.

The cases where there where there is no variation between the studies, \(\tau^2 = 0\), and some variation introduced by independent factors other than the measure of interest for a given study, \(\tau^2 =\) 0.2, 0.4 are provided.

# todo tau2

single-study simulation

For each of the 3 trials, a confidence interval, \(\theta \pm \Phi^{-1}(0.975)\mathcal \sqrt(V(\theta))\), was calculated, where \(\theta\) estimates the true measure, or log-ratio of control and intervention measures.
